{
  "text": "Previously, we suggested that TXNIP is highly expressed and acts as an antioxidant protein to regulate cellular ROS by activating p53 activity or by inhibiting p38 mitogen-activated protein kinase (MAPK) activity via direct interaction in hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Importantly, TXNIP-deficient mice are more glucose-tolerant than wild-type (WT) mice [CITATION_4] .",
